The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with everything that belongs to it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini-playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to the employees of Arch.Design since last year.
Arch.Design, the design and architecture firm from which a whole series of renowned Brno buildings originate, calculated the premises for its company mini-kindergarten from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint.
In wise foresight, because most of his 90 employees are in the Babyboom age and the company is interested in the project designers returning to their workplace as soon as possible.
Together with the possibility to work in a shorter way, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer to its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for the civil engineers to reconcile their demanding profession and child care.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The mini-kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from the European Social Fund and the Czech Republic State Budget.
Thanks to this financing (contributions of CZK 2, 8 million) the necessary facilities and equipment could be procured and for a period of 2 years qualified personnel and operation is provided.
After 2 years of funding, Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the Minikindergarten for 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the Economy Rating company providing active assistance in the implementation of the application.
The children are taken care of by fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, but the day alternates over several children.
The kindergarten business is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in relation to the use of the kindergarten - without regard to the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and care, the programme content in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the supporting programme of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, while also learning English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to children.
What's more - the presence of small children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus the stress is eliminated when the children are picked up late from a distant kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also emerging here.
Arch.Design thus joined the Czech companies, which offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Check out the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn-up fish mouths.
This is Casa Batlló by Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants the house with its organic forms got the nickname "Knobenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, the shed-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only when you take a closer look that you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thought-out order.
At night, the whole façade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colours.
The same sweeping lines and entwined forms also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-like shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and strips.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the reconstruction of a house dating from 1877, carried out by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but in the end he agreed with Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper conversion.
However, Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló apartment house alone.
He collaborated with architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner and the use of mosaics on the façade were his idea, especially on its drawing board.
However, numerous other painters and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed "Knobenhaus" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "cheering house".
It is also said that the sword of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted at the top of the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system for the house, which was unique at the time, with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
It's a bit bizarre, her 45-degree inclination already seems.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations at the time and did not allow himself to be deceived by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so horrified at the completion that they demanded remedy.
Among other things, the councillors also came up against the fact that the building with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, changes were no longer made, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the city's request to do so, Josep Batlló submitted an application to allow the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor was a social salon, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
By the basic elements of the conversion all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could chat comfortably, without having to renounce a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new façade, the house received a rather unusual roof and two more floors.
Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is covered and the courtyards are impressive.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
In doing so, he simply used the principle that white reflects light better than dark colours, which absorb sunlight on the contrary.
Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, is open to everyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is open to the public.
Only in the year did the homeowners decide on this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was discovered that this is a fairly profitable business, the visits were kept, yes, they were extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard handle, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the house dwellers and visit him at home.
