More and more parents want human surveillance devices to control the kids
The fear for their own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, which was originally invented for the search for cars, can locate people just as well, which would also be helpful in such cases, as recently when nine-year-old Anička Janatková disappeared without a trace.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette box but soon it should not be bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people have been frightened by the disappearance of Anička, so they are looking for ways and means to better protect their children.
Also for the price of compromising their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not about spying around, but about an effective way to reduce the likelihood of tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that there can be abuse of such devices in individual cases, for example when you put it in someone's pocket without knowing about it, but we have not had such a case so far."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child doesn't like to wear such a thing, he or she simply gets rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things when they don't want to be controlled."
"In the beginning, the mobile phones already raised great expectations among parents, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new monitoring devices," says Ms Bočková.
In their opinion, it is also controversial whether such an institution will actually help in the event of an attack.
"In planned kidnappings, the kidnapper virtually always checks whether the child has any electronics with him or her that could be used to locate it."
