The democracy movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil's influence is greater than that of the United States.
These were the results of the Latinobarómetro survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year's survey of September and October.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has been growing by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of supporters of democracy rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
In Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the sharp slump last year, such a trend can also be seen.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practice, as much as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Chart 3).
About 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% trust their government. Both values are similar to last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%) respectively.
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts to promote democracy.
The fact that this continued during the Great Depression may be due to the fact that the countries of Latin America experienced only a short period of recession and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were caught up by a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only marginally in 2009 and fell again by 32% this year.)
But there are strong differences in mood from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
This is less the case in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased.
Only for the second time since the start of the survey, many respondents in Latin America see crime in their country as a greater problem than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Approximately 31% say that either they or a family member have been the victims of a crime in the last year, but compared to 38% last year, the figures have fallen and thus reached the lowest level since 1995.
