A sloppy election
No one had expected that the elections in Haiti on 28 November would be perfect.
But the facts far exceeded the fears of the electoral assistants who hurried to help the thrashed country.
Overcrowded ballot boxes, multiple votes cast, ballot slips in the gutter, destroyed polling stations and intimidation were only a part of the problems.
The polling stations opened with hours of delay.
Many Haitians, many of whom had become homeless as a result of the earthquake in January, roamed around in search of an option.
Some eventually gave up completely.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some suspected leaders, demanded that the election results be lifted due to alleged fraud.
In the whole country, there were partial violent protests.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the head of the UN mission in Haiti, described the election "as quite good in many respects".
According to a cautious statement by observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, "these irregularities, however serious they may be, do not necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show goes on.
