The donor countries consider a legitimate, recognised government to be an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
The Haitians themselves agree.
Secretly in the middle
In the weeks following your husband’s sudden death, Argentina’s president, Cristina Fernández, experienced a wave of sympathy that pushed her popularity rate up by 20 points to over 50%. This is the highest value since her election in 2007.
However, whether this will help her to re-election next year depends on whether the visibly grieving Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her deceased husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs for this are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who continued to direct economic policy after his wife's election, often drew up budget plans that did not take full account of tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra income at their own convenience.
On paper, the Fernández government lost the majority in Congress last year.
But the opposition is divided and Kirchner's death after a heart attack on 27 October led to further rifts.
Some regime critics from the ruling Peronists stood behind Cristina Fernández.
However, after chaotic meetings (where one parliamentarian slapped another in the face and others accused the government of bribery), Congress failed to approve the 2011 budget.
"I will not discuss it," the President said.
The 2010 budget now also applies to the next year, giving the President even more opportunity to spend money at his own convenience.
The economy is running hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1%, but many private estimates - and wage demands of the trade unions - drive the value to almost 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was shaken by economic crises, declared growth and poverty reduction its main objectives, not the reduction of inflation.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, harassed the private sector, and cleaned the National Institute of Statistics and Census INDEC, which subsequently restored official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández take a more moderate path now?
It has called for talks between the private sector and trade union leaders.
And official statements suggest that wage increases will be limited to 18% next year.
The high world market prices for Argentina's agricultural products have given the economy a strong boost.
But inflation undermined the growth spurt of a major devaluement in 2002.
For this reason, Cristina Fernández may want to reconnect Argentina financially to the rest of the world.
Earlier this year, the government reached an agreement with securities holders that had rejected the country’s previous debt restructuring in 2001.
Now Fernández seems to be pushing for an agreement with the donors from the Paris Club, to which she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners had always rejected a review by the IMF, as usual elsewhere.
Last month, however, Minister of Economic Affairs Amado Boudou announced that the Fund will provide "technical support" for the creation of a new national consumer price index, which looks like the first step towards cleaning up INDEC.
It is not known whether Fernández will be politically active after the end of her term of office, even without the support of her husband.
If so, it needs the support of the middle class, which largely has enough of Kirchnerism.
When the Argentines return from their summer vacations in March, the wave of sympathies that has been brought to them will have deflated.
If she wants to win another election, she has to decide whether to lift many of her husband's political decisions quietly and quietly.
