Partisanity and polarization are greater today than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a wider ideological divide between Obama and the Congressional republicans than between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a pure prelude to a far more far-reaching election in 2012.
In this way, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator on the issues that still separate them from each other.
