China maintains its targets for reducing greenhouse gases
At COP16, China's representative said that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and that it would maintain its offer to cut 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China is holding its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, says Su Wei, the country's representative at COP16.
At his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations World Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He said that over the past four years his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he said that China would not change its objectives, but would work on this matter with the international community.
He explained that the Chinese climate change strategy is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress had been made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which included the objectives of reducing emissions of gases, he said.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China the state authorities had worked with the central state and the municipalities to achieve the goals of saving energy, using energy effectively and reducing emissions.
Moreover, he said, several multi-year plans have already been launched or completed, both those financed by the Chinese government and those who received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the effective use of energy programme introduced over the past five years, which had received United Nations (UN) investment, government investment and private ownership.
There is also a provincial climate change project, another on the exchange of traditional light bulbs through energy-saving bulbs, and another on mitigation and adaptation, he said.
Martin Krol, scientific government advisor on climate change in this country, confirmed that China’s efforts were far greater than was generally believed to be.
He pointed out that per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China amounted to six tonnes per person, while in the United States they amount to 100 tonnes. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to pollution.
