The US changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Prior to their meeting with the consulate, persons must present themselves to the visa application services, thereby reducing the cost of waiting times.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa at the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves to the visa application services (ASC, the initial letters in English) before talking to the consulate.
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be verified by the consulate before the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of handling the visa is decreasing, as it is no longer necessary to pay separately for the appointment, processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over.
The applicant shall make only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the counter to 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for handers and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not need to have a conversation at the consulate, they only have to introduce themselves to the nearest ASC, where they present their documents and their fingerprints are taken.
Since the biometric data are collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the conversation at the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for a visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer have to pay the 26 dollar service surcharge.
Additional information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassisy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
