Vengeful hackers and busy spies
The Affaire WikiLeaks has a dual meaning.
On one side it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at international level, and gives a foretaste of the future dominated by regression.
But let's go one by one.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that any file created by an intelligence agency (any nation) consists exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits throw nothing more than what was read over months in any journal anyway (except those whose owner is Berlusconi), and the horribly caricatured profile of Gaddafi had long been offering cabaret artists material for their sketches.
The rule according to which secret dossiers may only consist of news already known is essential for the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to Esothermal publications, you will realize that every work (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (or because he does not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe in nothing other than what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also the success mechanism of Dan Brown.
The same goes for the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited mind) is also the head of the secret service (otherwise he could be whatever, for example editor at Libération), who considers only what he acknowledges to be true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department was the same as those that Newsweek had already published the week before.
So why has such a fuss been made about the revelations of these dossiers?
On one side they say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies - at least since the end of the Second World War and since then also the heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some small representation tasks, have turned into espionage centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore this.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that an x-any hacker can tap into the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world holds the considerable blow against the prestige of the state department.
Moreover, the scandal puts less of the victims than the "sharpeners" into distress.
But let us devote ourselves to the profound nature of what happened.
Formerly, in Orwell's time, all power could be bundled like a Big Brother controlling every gesture of his subjects.
Since then Orwell's prophecy could have turned out to be perfectly correct, where you can control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the chosen highway and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But if one considers what is happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control process ceases to be one-sided and becomes circle-shaped.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the citizen's avenger - can discover the secrets of power.
But how can a power hold itself that is no longer able to keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free of secret because it reveals the public sphere; but to disclose in the style of WikiLeaks that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to deprive them of any power.
WikiLeaks did neither Sarkozy nor Merkel wrong, but Clinton and Obama did.
What will be the consequences of this insult inflicted on such a tremendous power?
It is obvious that in the future the states will no longer place any reserved information online - this would be like a hanging on the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that it is in vain with the current technologies to hope to keep confidential reports secret over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private relationships be maintained in the future, only for certain ears?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and romantic, but I feel compelled to imagine the government agents, moving in secret on uncontrollable marches, carrying their messages nowhere else but in mere memory, and also hiding the few written information they have received in the heels of their shoes.
The information would be stored in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, Watergate's espionage attempt had less success than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is progressing like cancer these days, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet reconstructs a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analogous) video cassettes had enabled the film researchers to explore a film band for band by reeling from back to front and uncovering all the secrets of montage, while the (numerical) CDs nowadays allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro portions.
The high-speed trains will take you from Rome to Milan within three hours, while this will take you three and a half hours by plane, including transfer.
It is therefore not unusual that politics and communication technology come back to cars and horses.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the messages.
At present, it is the embassies that demand confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France brightens up its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to look at the fast-moving financing promises (also called "fast start" or early funding) that have been made by developing countries.
And already the rough French fine speeches are revealed.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries have committed themselves to providing 30 billion dollars between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years, France 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU has drawn all the registers to convince its partners of the fact of their commitment to fast-start financing: detailed progress report of their Member States, press conference, major side events, leaflet distribution.
The transparency operation is remarkable and highly valued for its real value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it will have released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right track to pay tribute to its commitment of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look into detail, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" to ensure that an additional effort has been made without being detrimental to public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark that they consider best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen itself as the benchmark for 2009: international financing will be maintained and will add 150 million over three years to the "fast start" funding.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or in terms of ODA conditions.
In return, France felt that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 was "new and additional".
In other words, there are no indicative figures for expenditure in the previous year or at the global level of official development assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French support to developing countries can remain stable (or decrease) - France claims to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule about that yet, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, have €1 borrowed as equivalent to €1 donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often emission-reducing projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro as the equivalent of a donated euro... Moreover, only the cost of the loan to the investor country should be counted as a commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing else in mind than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% 36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself of this.
France is the only country in the EU that uses large amounts of loans.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) carry out 100% of their commitments with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to fulfil its obligations, France gives just 10 cents, meaning a comparable commitment.
Nice hocus pocus!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double swindle: partly with a further development of the action over time and partly with the reality of financial commitment.
France succeeds in making it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" millions in line with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a double negative effect; once within the EU (why do the other member states continue with the donation, if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing only a small question for a relatively short time compared to the totality of discussions on the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is essential to learn its lesson from this first year of early financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could bring forward discussions on the subject of long-term financing (another, crucial and currently discussed issue): one cannot escape the question of "predictability" or the method of recording its loans.
France could change its position to be as progressive as it is in other matters.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister, Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France's fast-start and its vision of "predictability" and the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
